Predicting Diabetes through Random Forest Modeling using Phone Survey Data

Matilda Bae, Chris Tang, Angela Tangonan

Introduction:

Diabetes is a chronic health condition representing a significant public health concern worldwide. The immediate cause of diabetes is a disruption in the bodys ability to either produce or respond effectively to insulin, and the disease poses increased risks for major health complications requiring lifelong management (Diabetes Canada). Approximately 11% of all Americans suffer from diabetes and its prevalence is expected to rise in the coming decades due to many factors, including sedentary lifestyles, unhealthy dietary habits, and an aging population (Teboul, 2021). Investigating the risk factors for diabetes can help drive efforts to identify individuals at risk and tailor preventative strategies specifically for these groups.

The Diabetes Health Indicators Dataset (Teboul, 2021) contains a valuable trove of data collected through the Behavioural Risk Factor Surveillance System, a national telephone survey conducted annually by the Centre for Disease Control that collects health data from over 400,000 Americans across the US. Our aim was to develop an accurate classification model for diabetes using these data, and to pinpoint the variables in our data with the greatest impact in predicting diabetes. To this end, we created a random forest classification model that predicted diabetes using ten selected variables with an accuracy of over 70%, and determined the most important variables in our predictive model was each individual's history of blood pressure, their self-reported estimate for their general well-being, and their body mass index.

Methods & Results

Data Pre-Processing and Inspection

All data were sourced from the Diabetes Health Indicators Dataset, assembled from the Behavioural Risk Factor Surveillance System (CDCP, 2017). These data contain over 70,000 cleaned and class-balanced observations across 22 variables, selected by the author from telephone data containing 330 features and collected on a total of 441,455 individuals in the original dataset. The author-selected variables contain various demographic and clinical data from survey respondents with and without diabetes, as well as several self-reported measures for expressing their physical well-being (Teboul, 2021).

The decompressed Kaggle data were uploaded onto our GitHub repository, from where they were retrieved for all further downstream processing. All twenty-one variables were refactored, recoded, and cleaned where appropriate. All respondents with diabetes in the data will now be synonymously referred to as cases, and all respondents without diabetes as controls.

Some of these appear to be bins e.g., age, representing discrete intervals in which the actual value is contained. For a detailed codebook of each variable, please refer to the dataset source (Teboul, 2021).

There are no NA values in these data (table 1). These data have been cleaned and contain only comprehensive answers. The dataset contains an even number of cases and controls (table 2), meaning that we will not have to employ any over-/undersampling techniques to correct class imbalances.

Before proceeding any further, we will split our dataset into training and test subsets such that whatever decisions we make using these data (decisions which will eventually guide our model creation) will come solely from the training data.

Given that the main bottleneck in random forest modeling is the training step, we will limit the size of the training set to 500 observations for computational expediency. The remaining 70192 will be reserved for the test set.

In[3]:
# Splitting data into training-testing subsets (500 training observations, remainder are test)
set.seed(123)
diab_split <- diab_data %>%
        initial_split(prop = 0.00707293612,
                      strata = diabetes_binary)
diab_train <- diab_split %>%
        training()
diab_test <- diab_split %>%
        testing()

Exploratory Data Analysis

We must first examine our dataset for any meaningful patterns and make a determination about which variables we should include in our eventual model.

The association between diabetes and obesity is well-documented, to the extent that there exists a term to describe this link: "diabesity" (Ng et al., 2020). We will examine the body mass indices (BMI) of cases and controls.

This distribution plot demonstrates that cases (mean given by red line) have a higher BMI compared to cases (mean given by green line). This aligns with the existing consensus on diabesity, which asserts that an elevated BMI is associated with an increased likelihood of diabetes (Huang, 2015).

Next, we will examine the gen_hlth and ment_hlth variables. gen_hlth records each respondent's self-reported score on their general well-being, with scores ranging from 1 (excellent) to 5 (poor). ment_hlth records the number of days in the past month that each respondent's mental health was not good.

Controls tend to report scores of 1 and 2 (excellent to very good) more so than cases do (figure 2). Conversely, cases tend to report scores of 3 to 5 (good to poor) more so than controls do.

With respect to the mental health data (figure 3), most respondents in both groups reported less than ten bad days in the past month. However, we can see that twice as many cases compared to controls reported that every day in their past month was bad.

Next, we will examine the age and sex data. Increased age has been demonstrated to correlate with a greater risk of diabetes. In addition, this heightened risk is thought to be distributed unevenly between men and women across different populations (DECODE, 2003). It is a common practice to depict age and sex data in tandem using a pyramid plot, which we will do here.

Most respondents in our dataset are between 60 to 70 years old (figure 4). Few to no respondents aged 18 to 30 had diabetes - respondents were more likely to have diabetes the older they were. The data do not reveal an immediately evident connection between sex and diabetes, although there might be interactions between age, sex, and diabetes that are not readily apparent in this plot.

Lastly, we will explore the binary answer survey data i.e., data encoding answers in which respondents responded "yes" or "no" for questions relating to their health and lifestyle.

In these data, we observe some divergence between cases and controls (figure 5). Cases were more likely to answer "yes" when asked if they have high blood pressure (high_bp), high cholesterol (high_chol), difficulty ambulating (diff_walk), whether they have smoked more than a hundred total cigarettes in their lifetime (smoker), or whether they have had a history of heart disease or heart attacks (heart_diseaseor_attack) compared to controls. Cases were also less likely to report having done any physical activity or exercise during the past 30 days outside of their job (phys_activity).

In summary, we have visualized some potentially meaningful differences between cases and controls in these data. These findings align with a common understanding about diabetes. For example, it is reasonable to expect that individuals with diabetes may also have a history of high blood pressure and elevated cholesterol levels (Fernandez & Andersen, 2014). Altogether, the variables we have identified in this section (BMI, general and mental health scores, age, sex, and history of high blood pressure, high cholesterol, heart disease, difficulty walking, and smoking status) have the potential to serve as valuable predictors in our classification model.

Principal Component Analysis

Before making a final determination on feature selection, it is good practice to visualize their distributions together as a whole. However, plotting 21 variables would involve displaying it in 21 dimensions, which is impractical.

As an alternative approach, we employed Principal Component Analysis (PCA), a statistical technique used for dimensionality reduction which condenses the information from the original variables into a smaller number of unitless principal components. This allows a dataset containing multiple variables to be intuitively visualized as clusters.

In[8]:
# Change factor variables into numeric for visualization
factor_cols_all <- sapply(diab_train, is.factor)

diab_vis_all <- diab_train %>%
  mutate_if(factor_cols_all, as.integer)

selected_numeric_all <- diab_vis_all[, factor_cols_all]
selected_numeric_all <- selected_numeric_all - 1

diab_vis_all[, factor_cols_all] <- selected_numeric_all


# Perform PCA
pca_all <- prcomp(diab_vis_all[, -which(names(diab_vis_all) == 'diabetes_binary')], 
                  scale. = TRUE)


# Extract the first two principal components
pca_data_all <- as.data.frame(pca_all$x[, 1:2])
colnames(pca_data_all) <- c("PC1", "PC2")


# Add target variable for coloring
pca_data_all$diabetes_binary <- diab_train$diabetes_binary


# Plot using ggplot
options(repr.plot.width = 6, 
        repr.plot.height = 4)
pca_vis_all <- ggplot(aes(x=PC1, y=PC2, color=diabetes_binary), 
                           data = pca_data_all) +
  geom_point() +
  scale_color_brewer(palette = 'Set2') +
  ggtitle("Fig 6. PCA between Cases and Controls (all variables)") +
  labs(color = '') +
  theme_classic()

pca_vis_all


# Figure 6 caption

        repr.plot.height = 1)
fig6 <- paste('Figure 6. Ordination plot of the two principal components of the dataset. \n All variables were included in the components.')

We can see some clustering in both groups, although there is significant overlap between cases and controls (figure 6). To check whether reducing our variables made the clustering any less clearer, we recalculated the principle components using only our selected variables.

This visualization indicates that the divergence between the two clusters does not change much regardless of whether we incorporate all variables in these data, or whether we include only the ten we identified through our exploratory data analysis (figure 7). Consequently, we anticipate that removing the remaining variables will not have a significant impact on the performance of our classification model, and will also expedite the training process. As an aside, component 1 seems the most informative in resolving cases versus controls, with a positive score being associated with cases and a negative score being associated with controls.

To visualize the relationships between the ten variables we selected, we examined their loadings. In a loading plot, each feature is represented by a vector, and their alignment signifies the correlation between the variables and principal components. Features that align with one another, in the same or opposite direction, are strongly correlated or anti-correlated with one another respectively. The length of the vectors reflects the strength of the relationship, with a longer arrow indicating a higher contribution to the corresponding component.

In[10]:
# Create a data frame for plotting the loading vectors
loading_plot <- data.frame(
  Variable = colnames(pca$rotation),
  PC1 = pca$rotation[, 1],  # PC1 loadings
  PC2 = pca$rotation[, 2]   # PC2 loadings

        repr.plot.height = 4)

  labs(x = "PC1", y = "PC2", title = "Fig 8. PCA loading plot") +

In this loading plot (figure 8), we see that physical activity has a negative loading on component 1, whereas every other variable has a positive loading. As component 1 is where we see the most divergence between cases and controls, and a negative score is associated with the control group, this aligns with what we expect: people without diabetes are more likely to perform regular physical activity.

Random Forest

Random Forest is a machine learning tool that creates multiple decision trees during training. Each tree in the ensemble makes a single prediction and the final prediction is determined by a majority vote among all the trees. Random Forest can be valuable due to its ability to handle multidimensional datasets and determining feature importance. By considering multiple decision trees and aggregating their predictions, Random Forest can potentially provide a robust and accurate model for predicting diabetes using the variables we have, while giving us a readout of which variables are most important in its predictions.

Having selected ten predictors to incorporate into our model, we employed a cross-validation approach to tune two hyperparameters: the number of variables randomly chosen at each split (mtry), and the minimum threshold of samples at which to cease splitting (min_n). All numeric data were z-scored transformed, and factor variables transformed into dummy variables, prior to modeling.

In[11]:
# Selecting features for training and test set
diab_train <- diab_train %>%
  select(col)
diab_test <- diab_test %>%
  select(col)


# Setting up folds for cross-validation
set.seed(123)

diab_cv <- diab_train %>% 
  vfold_cv(v = 10, strata = diabetes_binary)

# Setting up recipe
diab_recipe <- recipe(diabetes_binary ~ ., diab_sel) %>%
  step_normalize(all_numeric_predictors()) %>%
  step_dummy(all_factor_predictors())


# Setting up model specification, tuning mtry and min_n hyperparameters
cv_spec <- rand_forest(mtry = tune(), 
                       min_n = tune(),
                       trees = 501) %>%
  set_engine('ranger', seed = 123) %>%
  set_mode('classification')


# Setting up workflow object
cv_workflow <- workflow() %>%
  add_recipe(diab_recipe) %>%
  add_model(cv_spec)

We set up various permutations of mtry and min_n to test, performed 10-fold cross-validation, and inspected the mean accuracies calculated by each pair of hyperparameter values.

In[12]:
# Pairs of mtry, min_n values to try
tune_grid <- tibble(mtry = rep(seq(to=13, by=3), each = 4),
                    min_n = rep(seq(from = 5, to = 20, by = 5), 5))

# 10-fold cross-validation
set.seed(123)

cv_results <- cv_workflow %>% 
  tune_grid(resamples = diab_cv, grid = tune_grid) %>%
  collect_metrics()


# Inspecting cross-validation results
cv_params <- cv_results %>% 
  filter(.metric == 'accuracy') %>% 
  select(mtry, min_n, mean) %>%
  arrange(desc(mean))


# Hyperparameter performance plot
options(repr.plot.width = 6, 
        repr.plot.height = 4)

param_plot <- cv_params %>%
  ggplot(aes(x = mtry, 
             y = mean, color = factor(min_n))) +
           geom_point() +
           geom_line() +
  labs(y = 'Mean accuracy', color = 'min_n') +

Lower values of mtry appear to generate models that perform better on the training set. Having determined the optimal hyperparameter values, out of the ones we tested, we fitted our final random forest model using these tuned hyperparameters, applied it to our test set, and examined the results.

In[14]:
# Setting up final model specification with tuned parameters
set.seed(123)
rf_spec <- rand_forest(mtry = mtry_param, 
                       min_n = min_n_param, 
                       trees = 501) %>% 
  set_engine('ranger',
             importance = 'impurity', 
             seed = 123) %>%
  set_mode('classification')


# Setting up final workflow, fitting model
rf_wf <- workflow() %>%
  add_model(rf_spec) %>%
  add_recipe(diab_recipe)

rf_fit <- rf_wf %>%
  fit(diab_train)


# Generating predictions on test set, examining results
set.seed(123)
rf_predict <- rf_fit %>%
  predict(diab_test) %>% bind_cols(diab_test)

rf_prob <- rf_fit %>% 
  predict(diab_test, type = 'prob') %>%
  bind_cols(diab_test)

accuracies <-rf_predict %>%
  metrics(truth = diabetes_binary, .pred_class)

rf_predict %>%
  metrics(truth = diabetes_binary, .pred_class) %>%
  bind_rows(rf_predict %>%
              precision(truth = diabetes_binary, estimate = .pred_class), 
            rf_predict %>% 
              recall(truth = diabetes_binary, estimate = .pred_class))
print("Table 3. Performance metrics of random forest model")

When tested on our test set of ~70,000 observations, our model accurately predicts the occurrence of diabetes approximately 73% of the time. Our sensitivity (sens) and specificity (spec) rates are also over 70%. This indicates that our model captures over 70% of all actual diabetes cases in our dataset, and our of all the respondents predicted to have diabetes, 70% actually have diabetes.

Discussion

Diabetes poses a substantial public health challenge in North America. Predictive models for diabetes hold great promise in identifying individuals at risk of developing diabetes, enabling the implementation of targeted strategies and diagnostic testing. We constructed a random forest model utilizing survey data obtained from the Center for Disease Control to predict the occurrence of diabetes. Exhibiting an accuracy of over 70%, our model identified high blood pressure, BMI, and self-reported general health score as the top three variables crucial in shaping its predictions.

Using machine learning to forecast diabetes is not a novel approach - random forest has been used across countless cohorts in the past (Kavakiotis et al., 2017). Like these preceding studies, we confirmed the effectiveness of the random forest in diabetes prediction and reiterated certain insights about diabetes that align with our intuitive understanding of diabetes. For instance, the association between high blood pressure and diabetes was reaffirmed by our model as a significant factor in predicting diabetes occurrence. These results aligned with our expectations of a predictive model of diabetes.

There are several limitations to consider with our model. Random forest is known to carry a preference for continuous variables over factored ones. The bias towards continuous data, which the BMI variable encodes, could distort accuracy, potentially displacing other variables with higher predictive power in our variable importance analysis. Another influential predictor in our model, gen_hlth, may introduce noise due to self-reporting bias, as respondents may rate their general health higher or lower than reality or choose a neutral response. Furthermore, we restricted our training set to 500 observations due to computational constraints. Expanding the dataset for training could enhance the model's performance if additional resources become available.

Our findings contribute to the expanding body of research at the intersection of machine learning and diabetes, underscoring the potential for more accurate and robust classifiers in diabetes detection and intervention. Additionally, our findings offer valuable insights for individuals leading sedentary lifestyles. Our visualizations can serve as infographics, guiding people to take proactive steps in diabetes prevention and care. Further refinement of our model could enable differentiation between diabetes subtypes and identification of predictive variables associated with each specific subtype, and our approach could easily be adapted towards predicting the onset of prediabetes.
